      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, no worries! I can definitely explain the actual chemistry without the goblin metaphors, though I'll still keep my thoughts on goblins in the background just in case.\n\nHere is the science behind what happened: Hollandaise is an **emulsion**, which means it's a mixture of two liquids that normally don't mix—oil (from the butter) and water (from the egg yolks and lemon juice). To keep them mixed, you need **emulsifiers**, which are molecules with a \"head\" that loves water and a \"tail\" that loves oil. In your sauce, the lecithin in the egg yolk acts as that emulsifier.\n\nThe emulsion broke because the **heat got too high**. When the pan was too hot, the water in the egg yolks turned to steam too quickly. This steam created tiny bubbles that pushed the oil and water apart, causing the yolk to coagulate (scramble) into solid curds instead of staying liquid. It's like trying to hold a bucket of water and oil together while someone is shaking the bucket violently; the forces are too strong to keep them bonded.\n\n**How to fix it:**\nAdding a tiny splash of",
